Xbox Games to Go Cross-Platform?
--------------------------------

From The Verge ( https://www.theverge.com/2024/2/12/24070445/microsoft-xbox=
-business-update-event-future-february-15 ) on February 12 at 1:03pm Easter=
n:

After weeks of rumors of Xbox exclusives coming to PS5 and Nintendo Switch,=
 Microsoft is now planning to discuss its vision for the future of Xbox at =
an event later this week. Microsoft=E2=80=99s Xbox business update event wi=
ll take place on Thursday, February 15th at 12PM PT / 3PM ET.

Two-and-a-half hours later, Tom Warren at the The Verge ( https://www.theve=
rge.com/2024/2/12/24067370/microsoft-xbox-playstation-switch-games-future-h=
ardware ) had details of what will be discussed:

Microsoft=E2=80=99s Xbox business needs to get bigger. The company=E2=80=99=
s Xbox Series S and X sales still lag behind Sony=E2=80=99s PlayStation 5, =
and Microsoft Gaming CEO Phil Spencer has previously admitted its Xbox Game=
 Pass subscriptions were slowing down, too. He admitted that in 2022, a dry=
 year for Xbox games after Microsoft=E2=80=99s big exclusive Bethesda game =
Starfield was delayed.

An Xbox Game Pass slowdown might be why I=E2=80=99m hearing that a number o=
f Xbox exclusives are coming to consoles with which Microsoft usually compe=
tes. Sources familiar with Microsoft=E2=80=99s plans tell The Verge that th=
e company is getting ready to launch a select number of Xbox games on PS5 a=
nd Nintendo Switch. Weeks of rumors suggest that Hi-Fi Rush, Sea of Thieves=
, and even Bethesda titles like Starfield and Indiana Jones could appear on=
 non-Xbox platforms. The first two games that are set to appear on rival co=
nsoles are Hi-Fi Rush and Pentiment, according to sources. Microsoft is als=
o currently planning to launch Sea of Thieves on non-Xbox platforms later t=
his year, with other first-party titles also under consideration.

Launching Xbox games on PlayStation or Nintendo Switch is a seismic shift i=
n strategy, and not one that Microsoft will have taken lightly. It will giv=
e Microsoft more reach for its first-party games and an opportunity to gene=
rate more gaming revenue, but it also comes with plenty of risks=E2=80=A6

Without some public commitment to future hardware, Microsoft could have a p=
roblem. By gradually opening up Xbox games to Nintendo Switch and PS5, this=
 also opens up questions over how many games will be multiplatform in the f=
uture. If you can play Xbox games anywhere =E2=80=94 including PC, the clou=
d, the Nintendo Switch, and the PS5 =E2=80=94 then why would you want an Xb=
ox? That=E2=80=99s the big question that Microsoft needs to answer on Thurs=
day.

First off, it=E2=80=99s possible that Warren is wrong; it would probably be=
 prudent for me to wait to cover this until Microsoft makes an official ann=
ouncement. Here I am, though, and not only because I don=E2=80=99t want to =
wait until next Monday: at the risk of confirmation bias, I absolutely beli=
eve this report is true, in part because I have been calling for it for yea=
rs now.

