It is by focusing on the console world that one arrives at the conclusion t=
hat the Xbox, all things considered, is a success and something Microsoft c=
an hang its hat on. In fact, that=E2=80=99s exactly what nearly all Microso=
ft employees, from executives to rank-and-file, do whenever questioned if M=
icrosoft is innovative. =E2=80=9CLook at the Xbox! Look at Kinect!=E2=80=9D=
 is their refrain.

The problem is that winning at consoles is a small goal, one wholly differe=
nt from the reason Xbox was created in the first place. For many years now =
Microsoft has been focused on =E2=80=9CThree Screens and a Cloud,=E2=80=9D =
the idea that they as a platform provider ought to have a presence on your =
desk, in your pocket, and in your living room, all tied together by the clo=
ud. While that specific formulation arrived somewhere around 2009, that vei=
n of thinking was central to Xbox=E2=80=99s creation; the console aspects w=
ere meant to be a trojan horse, giving people a reason-to-buy the Xbox (and=
 not a Playstation); the more computer-type aspects would then be added ove=
r time until an Xbox was to living rooms what PCs were to every desk in eve=
ry office and every home (running Microsoft software).

It was this original goal that contributed to the current Xbox One disaster=
; Microsoft=E2=80=99s newest console is not only underpowered relative to t=
he PS4, it=E2=80=99s also $100 more expensive (due to the mandatory Kinect)=
, and launched with a terrible wave of publicity surrounding its always-on =
nature. The Kinect and connectedness were both included to help the Xbox On=
e fulfill its goal of being the primary box in your entertainment system, c=
ontrolling not just games but also live TV with your voice. Unfortunately, =
it doesn=E2=80=99t work that well for entertainment, even as it has hurt Mi=
crosoft=E2=80=99s ability to compete for console buyers. Thus, Microsoft ha=
s spent the last year walking back many of the main features of the console=
, including its DRM system, its connectedness, and, last week, offering the=
 console without the supposedly essential Kinect to make it $100 cheaper. N=
ow it=E2=80=99s the same price as a PS4, but still less powerful and with t=
he same dark cloud.

Here=E2=80=99s the bigger problem though: even if the Xbox One worked perfe=
ctly as an entertainment center, it would still cost $499. For those not go=
od at math, that=E2=80=99s $400 more than an AppleTV, and completely unappr=
oachable for anyone who does not care about gaming. In short, it is not eno=
ugh to consider how the Xbox is doing relative to consoles; the Xbox must b=
e evaluated based on how it is aligning with and contributing to Microsoft=
=E2=80=99s overall strategy, and in that light, it is an unmitigated disast=
er.

Two points a decade on: it=E2=80=99s interesting that the living room fight=
 still isn=E2=80=99t fully resolved. Amazon has arguably made the biggest p=
rogress with its Fire TV line of products, along with Roku; Google is a pla=
yer, and Apple still has the high end. That, though, only makes my overall =
point: it would have been better for Microsoft to focus on services and bei=
ng cross-platform. I had the chance to make that point later that year when=
 the company bought Minecraft ( https://stratechery.com/2014/microsofts-goo=
d-potentially-great-minecraft-acquisition/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1N=
