At our core, Microsoft is the productivity and platform company for the mob=
ile-first and cloud-first world. We will reinvent productivity to empower e=
very person and every organization on the planet to do more and achieve mor=
e.

At first glance, this statement seems to reference products like Office and=
 Azure, but it also works very well for Minecraft. Minecraft is more than j=
ust a game: it=E2=80=99s a community, with a huge cloud component, develope=
rs, and, at its very essence, it=E2=80=99s about making things. What could =
be more productive than that?

Moreover, like Office and Azure, Minecraft is truly cross-platform. It=E2=
=80=99s the best-selling paid-download game on both iOS and Android, and it=
 also has a very popular PS3 version and a newly-released PS4 version, with=
 a PS Vita port on the way. Xbox head Phil Spencer took care to note ( http=
://news.xbox.com/2014/09/games-minecraft-to-join-microsoft ) that this woul=
d remain the case:

Minecraft adds diversity to our game portfolio and helps us reach new gamer=
s across multiple platforms. Gaming is the top activity across devices and =
we see great potential to continue to grow the Minecraft community and nurt=
ure the franchise. That is why we plan to continue to make Minecraft availa=
ble across platforms =E2=80=93 including iOS, Android and PlayStation, in a=
ddition to Xbox and PC.

Here=E2=80=99s the thing, though: how much better would this acquisition lo=
ok if Microsoft didn=E2=80=99t own Xbox at all?

Microsoft, to its credit, avoided the big pitfall I was concerned about: Mi=
necraft has stayed resolutely cross-platform, and has not been leveraged to=
 sell more Xboxes. It is also still popular, with 140 million monthly activ=
e players last year, and a thriving mobile business. That, though, only mak=
es the Xbox question more pertinent: what exactly is the point?

