r7ShanoFuWcrc5DcgoS50nU7IuhjfDwYziBF904biqB5Zlsplp8QcIJP2TkRgltGwGHv0hIWtEK=
6W5g6bAcmp6uWLlmzHFy3VsYvKe3VfOTv9DQIBOQLXnb20WlL0XCZ7A97k6RAhrXpaAolboUPvP=
GBWmmiVFfqsAwvASNefW_uUs9b8k9Sp7XJGzsVCX74DWg1Uq6zURgCZfP_MfaA7lBfsnotxadAK=
w ) documented this change in the context of console history (and is, I thi=
nk, an essential read in light of this news); here are the pertinent paragr=
aphs:

Sony=E2=80=99s pivot after the (relatively) disappointing PlayStation 3 was=
 brilliant: if the economic imperative for 3rd-party developers was to be o=
n both Xbox and PlayStation (and the PC), and if game engines made that eas=
y to implement, then there was no longer any differentiation to be had in c=
atering to 3rd-party developers.

Instead Sony beefed up its internal game development studios and bought up =
several external ones, with the goal of creating PlayStation 4 exclusives. =
Now some portion of new games would not be available on Xbox not because it=
 had crappy cartridges or underpowered graphics, but because Sony could dec=
ide to limit its profit on individual titles for the sake of the broader Pl=
ayStation 4 ecosystem. After all, there would still be a lot of 3rd-party d=
evelopers; if Sony had more consoles than Microsoft because of its exclusiv=
es, then it would harvest more of those 3rd-party royalty fees.

The Xbox has never recovered from Sony=E2=80=99s pivot, and the Activision =
acquisition wasn=E2=80=99t going to change that: Sony bought burgeoning gam=
e studios that it could direct to make exclusives; Activision=E2=80=99s val=
ue is tied up in already-launched cross-platform franchises, which would be=
 economically ruinous to make exclusives.

Instead Microsoft=E2=80=99s gaming strategy was to compete on business mode=
l: what if you could subscribe to a library of games, instead of buy them i=
ndividually? Again from Consoles and Competition :

Microsoft is willing to cannibalize itself to build a new business model fo=
r video games, and it=E2=80=99s a business model that is pretty darn attrac=
tive for consumers. It=E2=80=99s also a business model that Activision woul=
dn=E2=80=99t pursue on its own, because it has its own profits to protect. =
Most importantly, though, it=E2=80=99s a business model that is anathema to=
 Sony: making titles broadly available to consumers on a subscription basis=
 is the exact opposite of the company=E2=80=99s exclusive strategy, which i=
s all about locking consumers into Sony=E2=80=99s platform.

The big question about the Game Pass strategy was what it meant for the Xbo=
x; one interpretation is that the long-term payoff was meant to be the same=
 payoff console makers have always been chasing: having the most popular co=
nsole, and thus capturing the most 3rd-party licensing fees. In this view G=
ame Pass was meant to be a reason-to-buy the Xbox, and while it didn=E2=80=
=99t make economic sense to make established cross-platform franchises from=
 Zenimax and Activision exclusive, it was worth doing just that for new gam=
es.

The other option was to view the Xbox as a regrettable necessity to keep So=
ny honest: in this world Microsoft would prefer to make Xbox Game Pass trul=
y cross-platform, which would mean running on PS5 and Switch, as well as mo=
bile, PCs, and the cloud; if Sony wasn=E2=80=99t interested, though, then M=
icrosoft needed to make a console to ensure there was a high-performance co=
nsole option for Xbox Game Pass subscribers.

Xbox=E2=80=99s Final Strategy
---------------------

That is a lot of context, but here is what I think happened:

* The Xbox One generation was designed to win the living room; it failed.
* I do think Microsoft gave thought to exiting gaming at that time, but dec=
ided to give the console business model (i.e. win a meaningful share and pr=
ofit from 3rd party developers) another shot with the Xbox Game Pass as a d=
ifferentiator. This resulted in the Series X and Series S; the latter was d=
esigned to be lower cost to give a lower price of entry to Xbox Game Pass, =
but it also made development for Xbox generally more difficult.
* Now I think that Microsoft is truly giving up on Xbox as a business drive=
r and, to the extent they stay in hardware, it is simply to provide an entr=
y point to Xbox Game Pass.

Giving up on exclusives is perfectly aligned with that final strategy: in t=
his view Microsoft is truly agnostic about what hardware you use, as long a=
s you are a Game Pass customer; and, if you don=E2=80=99t want to be a Game=
 Pass customer, then they will gladly take your money to defray the astrono=
mical costs that go into making modern games. 1 ( #fn1-0 )

This also gives rise to the single biggest question around this news: is Mi=
crosoft abandoning the console wars unilaterally, or will Xbox Game Pass be=
 allowed on the PS5? That=E2=80=99s the key thing about Microsoft=E2=80=99s=
 business model shift: it is oppositional to Sony as long as the intended p=
ayoff is selling more consoles, but it could just as easily be complementar=
y if the PS5 becomes a first-class citizen for Xbox Game Pass. Yes, Sony wo=
uld still have to be worried about cloud gaming in the long run, but that a=
pproach is constrained by the laws of physics; it seems unlikely that any P=
S5 customers are going to abandon consoles completely in favor of a cloud s=
ervice.

For the record, I think Microsoft is making the right decision whether or n=
ot there is some sort of impending deal with Sony; being a game publisher a=
nd cloud services provider is very much aligned with Microsoft=E2=80=99s ov=
erall strategy in the way that being a differentiated hardware provider is =
not. That it took them a decade to get to that point seems like a long time=
, but Xbox was a genuine point of pride for the company during its darkest =
days, and I can understand why it was given every chance to succeed. That i=
ts name might live on as one of the biggest publishers in the world, with a=
n innovative business model and leading cloud service, would be a suitable =
legacy.

